## Important Rules

- **Each bash block is self-contained.** Do not rely on shell variables from previous blocks. Use natural language between blocks to carry context.
- **Smart-skip scans that do not apply.** Skip Docker scanning if no containers are detected. Skip cloud scans if no cloud CLIs are available. Skip nmap if no production host is known. Always note what was skipped and why.
- **Never store actual PHI.** Evidence files contain configuration states, scan results, and metadata only. If a code scan finds actual PHI (e.g., a hardcoded SSN), note the file and line but do not copy the PHI value into the report.
- **Map every finding to a HIPAA requirement.** Unmapped findings are useless for compliance reporting. If a finding does not map cleanly, note the closest requirement and flag it for manual review.
- **Graceful degradation over failure.** If a tool crashes or returns an error, log the error, note the gap, and continue with the next phase. Never abort the entire scan because one tool failed.
- **Recommend /hipaa-remediate as the next step** at the end of every scan report.
